  "prompt": "What happens if you overdose on Naproxen?",
  "response": "Overdosing on naproxen, a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID), can be serious and requires immediate medical attention. Symptoms of a naproxen overdose might include:\n\n1. **Gastrointestinal Issues**: Nausea, vomiting, stomach pain, and ulcers or bleeding in the stomach or intestines, which may manifest as black or tarry stools or vomiting blood.\n\n2. **Central Nervous System Effects**: Drowsiness, dizziness, confusion, headache, or in severe cases, seizures and coma.\n\n3. **Cardiovascular Effects**: High blood pressure, slow heart rate, or even cardiac arrest in severe cases.\n\n4. **Respiratory Symptoms**: Difficulty breathing, wheezing, or respiratory depression.\n\n5. **Renal Damage**: Acute kidney failure, which could lead to decreased urine output and electrolyte imbalances.\n\n6. **Liver Damage**: Elevated liver enzymes, jaundice (yellowing of the skin or eyes), or liver failure in extreme cases.\n\n7. **Metabolic Disturbances**: Hyperkalemia (high potassium levels) or metabolic acidosis.\n\nIf someone is suspected of overdosing on naproxen, it is crucial to seek emergency medical help immediately or contact a poison control center. Treatment will depend on the severity of the overdose and may include activated charcoal to limit drug absorption, intravenous fluids, medications to protect the stomach lining, and supportive care to address any specific symptoms or complications.",
